5000|$|Keller’s {{first novel}} was highly praised by critics, {{including}} Michiko Kakutani in The New York Times, {{who said that}} in <b>Comfort</b> <b>Woman,</b> [...] "Keller has written a powerful book about mothers and daughters and the passions that bind generations." [...] Kakutani called it [...] "a lyrical and haunting novel" [...] and [...] "an impressive debut." [...] <b>Comfort</b> <b>Woman</b> won the American Book Award in 1998 and the 1999 Elliot Cades Award; previously, in 1995, Keller won the Pushcart Prize for a short story, [...] "Mother-Tongue", which became the second chapter of <b>Comfort</b> <b>Woman.</b> In 2003, she won the Hawai'i Award for Literature.|$|R
