40|$|Beloved and <b>Comfort</b> <b>Woman</b> {{have been}} {{analyzed}} {{using a variety}} of critical methodologies. One critical frame that has been absent from that dialogue is the academic discipline of trauma studies. Since these texts are written for and about national traumas, the theory oftrauma is a logical tool in which to unpack and advance the ideas imbedded within these texts. Trauma studies reveals how Beloved and <b>Comfort</b> <b>Woman</b> guard against the innate silencing tendencies ofthe traumatic experience. Through these texts, trauma speaks. More importantly, fixing the events oftrauma within Beloved and <b>Comfort</b> <b>Woman</b> ensures that national traumas are never forgotten. In short, each text prevents historical amnesia. Toni Morrison and Nora Okja Keller use literature as a vehicle in which to explore the absence of a traumatic listener and interrogate the difficulties in remembering an event that simultaneously confounds memorial. Each author recognizes the epistemological dilemma created in deciphering a past that is, by its traumatic nature, incomprehensible. Morrison and Keller confirm, in their character portrayals, that the very act ofliving through and testifying to the traumatic experience is invariably problematic. They illustrate the difficulties in understanding the unknowable and speaking the unspeakable. Each work mimics the clinical progression oftrauma, but more importantly, offers fresh ways to think about and understand the experience of trauma. Read next to and within the framework offered by trauma studies, Beloved and <b>Comfort</b> <b>Woman</b> can be reinterpreted and re-read not just as multicultural, postmodern narratives but as stories of and about trauma that advance the process of healing and survival...|$|R
25|$|Since the 1990s, Taiwanese {{survivors}} {{have been}} bringing {{to light the}} <b>comfort</b> <b>woman</b> issue in Taiwanese society, and gaining support from women's rights activists and civil groups. Their testimony and memories have been documented by newspapers, books, and documentary films.|$|R
